sections.paragraphs:
Mackenzie was born on 28 January 1822 in Logierait, Perthshire, Scotland, the son of Mary Stewart (Fleming) and Alexander Mackenzie, Sr., who were married in 1817.{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} The site of his birthplace is known as Clais-'n-deoir "The Hollow of the Weeping", where families said their goodbyes as the convicted were led to nearby Gallows Hill. The house in which he was born was built by his father and is still standing in 2019. He was the third of 10 boys, seven of whom survived infancy.{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} Alexander Mackenzie, Sr., was a carpenter and ship's joiner who had to move around frequently for work after the end of the Napoleonic Wars in 1815. Mackenzie's father died on 7 March 1836 and at the age of 13, Alexander Mackenzie, Jr., was thus forced to end his formal education to help support his family. He apprenticed as a stonemason and met his future wife, Helen Neil, in Irvine, where her father was also a stonemason.{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} The Neils were Baptist and shortly thereafter, Mackenzie converted from [[Presbyterianism]] to [[Baptist]] beliefs.{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} Together with the Neils, he immigrated to Canada in 1842 to seek a better life. Mackenzie's faith was to link him to the increasingly influential [[temperance cause]], particularly strong in [[Canada West]] where he lived, a constituency of which he was to represent in the [[Parliament of Canada]].{{sfnp|Forster|1990}}

The Neils and Mackenzie settled in Kingston, Ontario. The limestone in the area proved too hard for his stonemason tools, and not having money to buy new tools, Mackenzie took a job as a labourer constructing a building on Princess Street.{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} The contractor on the job claimed financial difficulty, so Mackenzie accepted a promissory note for summer wages. The note later proved to be worthless. Subsequently, Mackenzie won a contract building a bomb-proof arch at [[Fort Henry, Ontario|Fort Henry]]. He later became a foreman on the construction of Kingston's four [[Martello tower|Martello Towers]] - [[Murney Tower]], [[Fort Frederick (Kingston, Ontario)|Fort Frederick]], [[Cathcart Tower]], and [[Shoal Tower]]. He was also a foreman on the construction of the [[Welland Canal]] and the [[Lachine Canal]]. While working on the [[Beauharnois Canal]], a one-ton stone fell and crushed one of his legs. He recovered, but never regained the strength in that leg. While in Kingston, Mackenzie became a vocal opponent of religious and political entitlement and corruption in government.

Mackenzie married Helen Neil (1826–52) in 1845 and with her had three children, with only one girl, Mary, surviving infancy.{{sfnp|Harris|1893|p=136}} Helen and he moved to Sarnia, Ontario (known as Canada West) in 1847 and Mary was born in 1848.{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} They were soon joined from Scotland by the rest of Mackenzie's brothers and his mother.{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} He began working as a general contractor, earning a reputation for being a hard-working, honest man, as well as having a working man's view on fiscal policy. Mackenzie helped construct many courthouses and jails across southern Ontario. A number of these still stand today, including the Sandwich Courthouse and Jail now known as the [[Windsor, Ontario|Mackenzie Hall Cultural Centre]] in Windsor, Ontario, and the [[Chatham Jail|Kent County Courthouse and Jail]] in Chatham, Ontario. He even bid, unsuccessfully, on the construction of the Parliament buildings in Ottawa in 1859. Helen died in 1852, finally succumbing to the effects of excessive doses of mercury-based calomel used to treat a fever while in Kingston. In 1853, he married [[Jane Mackenzie|Jane Sym]] (1825–93).{{sfnp|Harris|1893|p=136}}

[[Image:Mason overseer.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|An 1875 ''[[Canadian Illustrated News]]'' cartoon shows Mackenzie the Mason and Governor General [[Lord Dufferin]] the Overseer.]]

Mackenzie's first biography in 1892 referred to him as Canada's Stainless Statesman.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|loc=dedication introduction}} Here are a number of other references to his character. He was a devout Baptist and teetotaller who found refuge in, and drew strength from, his family, friends, and faith.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|pp=55, 93,100}}{{sfnp|Forster|1990}} He was also a loyal friend and an incorrigible prankster (stuffed chimney on young in-laws; rolled boulder down Thunder Cape towards friend A. McKellar; burned Tory campaign placards in hotel woodstove early in morning).{{sfnp|Thomson|1960|pp=18, 87}} Unpretentious and down to earth,{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|pp=99, 633, 660}} his public official austerity was in striking contrast to private compassion and giving nature.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|pp=99-100}} He was the soul of honour and integrity,{{sfnp|Marquis|1903|p=401}} a proud man who sought no recognition or personal enrichment and accepted gifts reluctantly.{{sfnp|Thomson|1960|pp=354, 367}} He preferred to follow than lead (unreferenced - many times he refused leadership offers) and often found duty outweighed heavy burden of office.<ref>{{harvp|Thomson|1960|p=343}}; {{harvp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|pp=294, 441, 631}}</ref> He was uncompromising on his principles, perhaps too much so.<ref>{{harvp|Marquis|1903|p=460}}; {{harvp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|pp=211, 518}}; {{harvp|Forster|1990}}</ref> An historian at the time said, “He was, and ever will remain, the Sir Galahad of Canadian politics.”{{sfnp|Marquis|1903|p=418}}

Very proud of his Scottish heritage, he was forever a Scot “''Nemo me impune lacessit''” (no one attacks me with impunity).{{sfnp|Ross|1913|p=56}} The Upper Canada rebellion leader [[William Lyon Mackenzie|W.L. Mackenzie]] referred to him, “He is every whit a self-made, self-educated man. Has large mental capacity and indomitable energy.” {{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=120}} Canada's Governor General, Lord Dufferin, said of him, he is “as pure as crystal, and as true as steel, with lots of common sense.”{{sfnp|Thomson|1960|p=211}} A close friend, [[Chief Justice of Canada|Chief Justice]] [[Louis Henry Davies|Sir Louis Davies]], said he was “the best debater the House of Commons has ever known.” <ref>(Mackenzie's newspaper scrapbook "Days of Giants", Library and Archives Canada).</ref> A friend and colleague in Cabinet who went on to become prime minister of Canada, Sir [[Wilfrid Laurier]], said he was “one of the truest and strongest characters to be met within Canadian history. He was endowed with a warm heart and a copious and rich fancy, though veiled by a somewhat reticent exterior, and he was of friends the most tender and true.”{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=633}} Another friend and colleague, who went on to become premier of Ontario, Sir [[George William Ross|George Ross]], said, “Mackenzie was ''sui generis'' a debater. His humorous sallies blistered like a blast from a flaming smelter. His sterling honesty is a great heritage, and will keep his memory green to all future generations.”{{sfnp|Ross|1913|p=31}} At his eulogy, Rev. Dr. Thomas compared him to the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]], who “stood four square, to all the winds that blow.”{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=643, quoting Tennyson’s "Ode to the Death of the Duke of Wellington"}}

Newspaper around the world and in Canada had this to say about him. ''The London Times'' – the untiring energy, the business-like accuracy, the keen perception and reliable judgment, and above all the inflexible integrity, which marked his private life, he carried without abatement of one jot into his public career.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=663}} ''The Westminster Review'' – a man, who although, through failing health and failing voice, he had virtually passed out of public life, yet retained to the last the affectionate veneration of the Canadian people as no other man of the time can be said to have done.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=651}}<ref>{{cite book |title=The Westminster Review |volume=Volume 137 |date=1892 |location=London |publisher=Edward Arnold |page=651 |url=https://archive.org/details/westminsterrevi07unkngoog/page/n672}}</ref>  The ''Charlottetown Patriot'' – in all that constitutes the real man, the honest statesman, the true patriot, the warm friend, and sincere Christian, he had few equals. Possessed of a clear intellect, a retentive memory, and a ready command of appropriate words, he was one of the most logical and powerful speakers we have ever heard.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=662}} The''St. John Telegraph'' – he was loved by the people and his political opponents were compelled to respect him even above their own chosen leader. As a statesman, he has had few equals.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=660}} The ''Montreal Star'' – it is one of the very foremost architects of the Canadian nationality that we mourn. In the dark days of ’73, Canadians were in a state of panic, distrusting the stability of their newly-built Dominion; no one can tell what would have happened had not the stalwart form of Alexander Mackenzie lifted itself above the screaming, vociferating and denying mass of politicians, and all Canada felt at once, there was a man who could be trusted.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=661}} The ''Toronto Globe'' – he was a man who loved the people and fought for their rights against privilege and monopoly in every form.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=661}} The ''Philadelphia Record'' – Like Caesar, who twice refused a knightly crown, Alexander Mackenzie refused knighthood three times. Unlike Caesar, he owed his political overthrow to his incorruptible honesty and unswerving integrity.{{sfnp|Buckingham|Ross|1892|p=660}}

